+  /** Run `body` on a dedicated large-stack thread and return its result. Both the
+   *  frontend (`compile`, which VM-evaluates the self-hosted tower over the whole
+   *  source) and the program run (`runVm`/`runBytecode`) recurse on the depth of
+   *  the CoreIR tree — a deeply nested `.ssc` (e.g. scljet's byte codecs / SQL
+   *  engine) overflows the default CLI thread stack. Isolating the deep stack here
+   *  keeps a huge `-Xss` off every other (server/actor) thread. */
+  // Reserved (lazily committed) stack for the frontend + program run. Both recurse
+  // on CoreIR-tree depth; a large self-hosted program (scljet's SQL engine) needs a
+  // big stack, and the INTERPRETED worst case (parallel CPU contention keeps the JVM
+  // from JIT-compiling the interpreter, so frames are far larger) needs more still.
+  // Overridable via -Dssc.native.stack.mb for tuning.
+  private val LargeStackBytes =
+    Option(System.getProperty("ssc.native.stack.mb")).flatMap(_.toLongOption)
+      .getOrElse(1024L) * 1024L * 1024L
+
+  private def onLargeStack[A](threadName: String)(body: => A): A =
+    val result  = new java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicReference[A]()
+    val failure = new java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicReference[Throwable]()
+    val task = new Runnable:
+      def run(): Unit =
+        try result.set(body)
+        catch case t: Throwable => failure.set(t)
+    val thread = new Thread(null, task, threadName, LargeStackBytes)
+    thread.start()
+    thread.join()
+    val err = failure.get()
+    if err != null then throw err
+    result.get()
+
   /** `run-js --v2` on the native lane: native ssc1 front → CoreIR → v2 JsGen →
